description: From Middle English [Term?], compare French jobard (“gullible, crazy”) and English noll (“head”).

entries.meaning: A person's head, particularly if misshapen or blocky.
examples: [She...] bathed his jobbernowl thrice in the fountain; then threw a handful of meal on his phiz [...]
“And a noodle and a jolt-head; you’re a jobbernowl and a doodle, a maundering mooncalf and a block-headed numps, a gaby and a loon; you’re a Hatter!” I shrieked the last epithet.
